</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="174" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,496,151,176]" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Cope, 1868" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1868" box="[503,785,151,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="23" pageNumber="174" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="percarinatum">
<emphasis box="[503,785,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Loxopholis percarinatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to, and widespread in, 
<taxonomicName box="[1171,1289,151,176]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="23" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,222,188,213]" name="Brazil" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[234,344,188,213]" name="Suriname" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Suriname</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[357,447,188,212]" name="Guyana" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[459,577,188,213]" name="Venezuela" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[637,688,189,212]" name="Peru" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[704,789,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1930,1952]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,672,1899]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,662,1908]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 14. Distribution of examined material of Loxopholis percarinatum and Micrablepharus maximiliani." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581989/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Aguayo &amp; Muñoz (2008) also reported it from 
<collectingCountry box="[1347,1433,188,213]" name="Bolivia" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[183,254,223,248]" name="Brazil" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[611,695,224,248]" country="Brazil" name="Amapa" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Amapá</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[707,760,224,248]" country="Suriname" name="Para" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Pará</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[773,889,223,248]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Maranhão</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[902,1013,223,248]" country="Brazil" name="Tocantins" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Tocantins</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1025,1146,224,248]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1159,1258,223,248]" country="Brazil" name="Roraima" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Roraima</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1271,1383,223,248]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[151,302,260,284]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cope, 1868" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1868" box="[314,599,260,285]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="23" pageNumber="174" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="percarinatum">
<emphasis box="[314,599,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Loxopholis percarinatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits primary and secondary terra firme and flooded (varzea) forests, and swampy areas, where it is found among leaf litter (Vitt 
<emphasis box="[1090,1146,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
1999; Molina 
<emphasis box="[1310,1365,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2004; Barrio-Amorós 
<emphasis box="[329,377,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">et al</emphasis>
. 2011; Waldez 
<emphasis box="[551,607,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2013). Even though it occurs in a variety of environments, it is frequently found along shaded water edges (
<collectingCountry box="[539,614,367,392]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Cunha</collectingCountry>
1961; Hoogmoed 1973; Martins 1991b; Ávila-Pires 1995; Vitt &amp; Zani 1998; Vitt 
<emphasis box="[270,327,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">et al.</emphasis>
2008).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
